---

## 1. Model Details

> What model or API is being used? Who built it? What version? What type of
> model — classification, prediction, generation, optimization? When was it
> developed?

[The NutriGuide system is an AI recommendation system combining collaborative filtering and constraint-based optimization to generate personalized weekly meal plans and shopping lists. It is trained on nutritional databases, grocery pricing data, and dietary guidelines.

The system also incorporates a natural language processing (NLP) component to support basic user queries.

It was developed by a university research team in partnership with a nonprofit organization focused on food security, and funded through a USDA grant. A specific model version is not provided, which shows that this is an early-stage or pilot deployment system.]

---

## 2. Intended Use

> What is the primary task? Who are the intended users? What decisions does
> the system inform? In what context is it deployed?

[This system is meant to be a healthy food recommendation system, specifically meant to help low income families in underserved urban neighborhoods in order to enable them make healthy food choices. The primary users of the tool are parents, caregivers in household earning below 200% of the federal poverty level. 
The system informs decisions related to: Weekly meal planning, Grocery purchasing within budget constraints, Healthier food substitutions. It is deployed as a mobile application and kiosk-based system in community health centers and WIC offices.]

---

## 3. Out-of-Scope Uses

> What should this system NOT be used for? What populations, settings, or
> decisions are outside its design? What misuses are foreseeable?

[It would be inappropriate for anyone to try to use this tool, which is a healthy food recommendation system to manage any chronic conditions that they may be battling with; like heart diseases or type 2 diabetes. That would mean that the tool is being used in the wrong context for the wrong purpose. Also, currently, the tool does not fully handle cultural food preferences so expecting the tool to provide tailor-made recommendations based on one's cultural preferences would be out of the tool's scope.]

---

## 4. Training Data

> What data was used to build or train this model? How was it collected? What
> populations, geographies, languages, and time periods does it cover? What
> is missing?

[The system draws on the USDA Food Central Database for nutritional information, Local grocery store pricing APIs where available, Food bank inventory (which is updaated weekly), user interaction data which is collected through the app. The training data for the collaborative filtering model comes from a prior 18-month pilot in Philadelphia that involved approximately 2400 households.]

---

## 5. Evaluation Data & Metrics

> How was performance measured? What metrics were used — accuracy, sensitivity,
> specificity, F1, AUC, RMSE? On what test set? Is it independent from the
> training data?

[No formal evaluation framework is described in the system documentation. Current feedback mechanisms rely on user ratings and substitution behavior, which are insufficient for rigorous validation.

Recommended evaluation metrics include:
Recommendation accuracy (precision/recall)
User adherence rate (did users follow meal plans?)
Nutritional adequacy scores
Cost-efficiency metrics (nutrition per dollar)
User satisfaction scores (beyond simple ratings)

Also, an independent test dataset separate from training data should be used to evaluate this performance.]

