## 8. Limitations & Caveats

> Known failure modes, edge cases, what the model does not capture. Conditions
> where it performs poorly. Assumptions baked into the design that may not
> hold in all deployment contexts.

[One major limitation of the tool is that it lacks cultural context or consideration. If the tool recommends a meal that they cannot really relate to, that recommendation will become useless to the users. Also, it currently does not account for other food allergies but just 6. That can be a problem if some individuals have other allergies aside the 6 that the tool covers.]
Limited handling of cultural food preferences
Only accounts for six major allergens, missing others
Assumes consistent access to certain food sources (which may not exist)
Dependent on data quality (pricing, inventory, user input)
May not adapt well to rapid price fluctuations or supply shortages
Designed primarily for urban settings, limiting generalizability
---

## 9. Human Oversight

> Who reviews outputs before action is taken? Human in the loop, on the loop,
> or out of the loop? What is the escalation path when the model is wrong?
> Can it act autonomously — and should it?

[Another limitation of this tool is that it lacks human oversight. There is no dietitian or nutritionist that serves as the human in the loop to ensure that the meals or foods recommended are safe for these families. This tool should not be aloud to work autonomously, there has to be a form oversight.]
Currently, there is no explicit human-in-the-loop system for validating recommendations.

Recommended approach:

Incorporate dietitians or nutritionists as reviewers (human-in-the-loop)
Community health workers could act as on-the-loop supervisors during WIC visits
Provide an escalation pathway for:
Allergy concerns
Medical dietary needs
Incorrect recommendations

The system should not operate fully autonomously, especially given its impact on health.
